### Describe the bug
I run a Blazor WASM app that uses MSAL for Azure AAD B2C auth, and can call into my ASP.net web api. Whenever the user is not authenticated and Blazor app tries to make a call to secured api via configured httpClient it results in a NullReferenceException being thrown, instead of expected AccessTokenNotAvailableException.
StackTrace:
```
         at Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.WebAssembly.Authentication.AuthorizationMessageHandler.SendAsync(HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
         at Microsoft.Extensions.Http.Logging.LoggingScopeHttpMessageHandler.SendAsync(HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
         at System.Net.Http.HttpClient.SendAsyncCore(HttpRequestMessage request, HttpCompletionOption completionOption, Boolean async, Boolean emitTelemetryStartStop, CancellationToken cancellationToken)

```

I have narrowed it down to this bit of code:
 ```
 var tokenResult = _tokenOptions != null ?
      await _provider.RequestAccessToken(_tokenOptions) :
      await _provider.RequestAccessToken();

  if (tokenResult.TryGetToken(out var token))
  {
      _lastToken = token;
      _cachedHeader = new AuthenticationHeaderValue("Bearer", _lastToken.Value);
  }
  else
  {
      throw new AccessTokenNotAvailableException(_navigation, tokenResult, _tokenOptions?.Scopes);
  }
```

Basically when the user is not authenticated the tokenResult I get from provider will for whatever reason still have a success status, yet the inner token in that result is null. TryGetToken method on AccessTokenResult will only check for success status and will return true even if the token is null:

```
  public bool TryGetToken(out AccessToken accessToken)
  {
      if (Status == AccessTokenResultStatus.Success)
      {
          accessToken = _token;
          return true;
      }
      else
      {
          accessToken = null;
          return false;
      }
  }
```

So naturally, when it proceeds in the 1st bit of code it will pass the if statement and try to get a value from a null token, resulting in a NullReferenceException:

`_cachedHeader = new AuthenticationHeaderValue("Bearer", _lastToken.Value); // _lastToken is null here`

I may be wrong and it is an expected behavior, but according to documentation making a call to a secure API should result in a AccessTokenNotAvailableException instead of NullReferenceException.
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/blazor/security/webassembly/additional-scenarios?view=aspnetcore-5.0#attach-tokens-to-outgoing-requests

### To Reproduce

- Create a project via dotnet command described here: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/blazor/security/webassembly/hosted-with-azure-active-directory-b2c?view=aspnetcore-5.0
`dotnet new blazorwasm -au IndividualB2C --aad-b2c-instance "{AAD B2C INSTANCE}" --api-client-id "{SERVER API APP CLIENT ID}" --app-id-uri "{SERVER API APP ID URI}" --client-id "{CLIENT APP CLIENT ID}" --default-scope "{DEFAULT SCOPE}" --domain "{TENANT DOMAIN}" -ho -o {APP NAME} -ssp "{SIGN UP OR SIGN IN POLICY}"`

- In Client/Pages/FetchData.razor remove "[Authorize]" attribute
- Run project
- Navigate to fetch data while being unauthenticated
- Unhandled NullReferenceException exception is thrown

### Exceptions (if any)
NullReferenceException

### Further technical details
- Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.WebAssembly 5.0.3
- Microsoft.Authentication.WebAssembly.Msal 5.0.3

